In [[neuroscience]], the '''critical brain hypothesis''' states that certain [[Biological neural network|biological neuronal networks]] work near [[phase transition]]s.<ref name=":0">Ludmila Brochini, Ariadne de Andrade Costa, Miguel Abadi, Antônio C. Roque, Jorge Stolfi, Osame Kinouchi. Phase transitions and self-organized criticality in networks of stochastic spiking neurons. Available at:https://arxiv.org/pdf/1606.06391v1.pdf</ref><ref>Chialvo, D. R. Emergent complex neural dynamics. Nature Physics 6, 744–750 (2010).</ref><ref>Hesse, J. & Gross, T. Self-organized criticality as a fundamental property of neural systems. Criticality as a signature of healthy neural systems: multi-scale experimental and computational studies (2015)</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chialvo|first=D. R.|last2=Bak|first2=P.|date=1999-06-01|title=Learning from mistakes|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0306452298004722|journal=Neuroscience|volume=90|issue=4|pages=1137–1148|doi=10.1016/S0306-4522(98)00472-2|arxiv=adap-org/9707006}}</ref> Experimental recordings from large groups of neurons have shown bursts of activity, so-called neuronal avalanches, with sizes that follow a [[power law]] distribution. These results, and subsequent replication on a number of settings, led to the hypothesis that the collective dynamics of large neuronal networks in the brain operates close to the [[critical phenomena|critical point]] of a [[phase transition]].<ref name=Beggs2012>Beggs, John M., Timme, Nicholas. Being critical of criticality in the brain. Frontiers in Physiology, 07, June 2012</ref> According to this hypothesis, the activity of the brain would be continuously transitioning between two phases, one in which activity will rapidly reduce and die, and another where activity will build up and amplify over time.<ref name=Beggs2012/> In criticality, the [[brain]] capacity for information processing is enhanced,<ref name="Beggs2012" /><ref>Kinouchi, O. & Copelli, M. Optimal dynamical range of excitable networks at criticality. Nature Physics 2, 348–351 (2006).</ref><ref>Beggs, J. M. The criticality hypothesis: how local cortical networks might optimize information processing. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences 366, 329–343 (2008).</ref><ref>Shew, W. L., Yang, H., Petermann, T., Roy, R. & Plenz, D. Neuronal avalanches imply maximum dynamic range in cortical networks at criticality. The Journal of Neuroscience 29, 15595–15600 (2009).</ref> so subcritical, critical and slightly supercritical branching process of thoughts could describe how human and animal minds function.<ref name=":0" />
==History==
Discussion on the brain's criticality have been done since 1950, with the paper on the imitation game for a Turing test.<ref>Turing, A. M. Computing machinery and intelligence. Mind 59, 433–460 (1950).</ref> In 1995, Herz and Hopfield noted that self-organized criticality (SOC) models for earthquakes were mathematically equivalent to networks of integrate-and-fire neurons, and speculated that perhaps SOC would occur in the brain.<ref>Herz, A. V. & Hopfield, J. J. Earthquake cycles and neural reverberations: collective oscillations in systems with pulse-coupled threshold elements. Physical Review Letters 75, 1222 (1995).</ref> Simultaneously Stassinopoulos and Bak proposed a simple neural network model working at criticality<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stassinopoulos|first=Dimitris|last2=Bak|first2=Per|date=1995-05-01|title=Democratic reinforcement: A principle for brain function|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevE.51.5033|journal=Physical Review E|volume=51|issue=5|pages=5033–5039|doi=10.1103/PhysRevE.51.5033|bibcode=1995PhRvE..51.5033S}}</ref> which was expanded latter by Chialvo and Bak.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chialvo|first=D.R.|last2=Bak|first2=P.|title=Learning from mistakes|url=https://doi.org/10.1016/S0306-4522(98)00472-2|journal=Neuroscience|volume=90|issue=4|pages=1137–1148|doi=10.1016/s0306-4522(98)00472-2|arxiv=adap-org/9707006}}</ref> In 2003, the hypothesis found experimental support by Beggs and Plenz<ref>Beggs, J. M. & Plenz, D. Neuronal avalanches in neocortical circuits. The Journal of Neuroscience 23, 11167–11177 (2003).</ref>. The critical brain hypothesis is not a consensus among the scientific community.<ref name=Beggs2012/>
